There is an Assisted Living Programs Board established to:
develop statewide policy on assisted living programs;
coordinate agency responsibility for implementation of policies and programs related to assisted living;
review and approve policies and regulations governing assisted living programs; and
establish appropriate interagency agreements relative to assisted living programs.

The Board consists of 15 voting members as follows:
the Secretary of Health and Mental Hygiene;
the Secretary of Human Resources;
the Secretary of Aging; and
the following voting members appointed by the Governor with the advice and consent of the Senate:
one representative of the Disability Law Center;
one representative of a small program that was certified as a sheltered housing project by the Department of Aging as of December 31, 1995, or could have been certified as a sheltered housing project by the Department of Aging if it had been in existence on December 31, 1995;
one representative of a small program that was certified as a care program by the Department of Human Resources as of December 31, 1995, or could have been certified as a care program by the Department of Human Resources if it had been in existence on December 31, 1995;
one representative of a small program that was licensed or registered as a domiciliary care program by the Department of Health and Mental Hygiene as of December 31, 1995, or could have been licensed or registered as a domiciliary care program by the Department of Health and Mental Hygiene if it had been in existence on December 31, 1995;
four consumer members;
one representative of the Assisted Living Facilities Association of America;
one representative of the Maryland Association of Nonprofit Homes for the Aging;
one representative of the Health Facilities Association of Maryland; and
one representative of the Long-Term Care Association.
